<blue>1</blue><e2>Blair </e2>not happy with new green deal The <e3>British </e3>Prime Minister , <e2>Tony </e2><e2>Blair </e2>, disagreed yesterday with <e1><eC>Australia </eC></e1><e1><eC>'s </eC></e1>decision to sign a climate change deal with <e13><eC>the </eC></e13><e13><eC>United </eC></e13><e13><eC>States </eC></e13>. <br><blue>2</blue>The Federal Government denied that the agreement , signed this week , was a signal it was dumping the Kyoto Protocol on greenhouse gases . <br><blue>3</blue>The Australian-US `` climate action partnership '' involves liaison between governments , businesses and research bodies on climate change . <br><blue>4</blue>Critics say that on the one hand <e1>Australia </e1>is saying it does not want to dump <e10><eC>Kyoto </eC></e10>, yet on the other <e10><eC>it </eC></e10>is cosying up to <e13><eC>the </eC></e13><e13><eC>US </eC></e13>- which does want to dump <e10>Kyoto </e10>. <br><blue>5</blue><e1><eC>Australia </eC></e1><e1><eC>'s </eC></e1>involvement in <e10>Kyoto </e10>has been in doubt ever since the <e13><eC>US </eC></e13>President , <e7>George </e7><e7>Bush </e7>, announced last year that ratifying the protocol would hurt the <e13>US </e13>economy . <br><blue>6</blue>The future of the protocol , which sets targets for all countries in an attempt to cut pollution , will be decided this year at a meeting in <e8>Johannesburg </e8>. <br><blue>7</blue><e5><eC>A </eC></e5><e5><eC>spokeswoman </eC></e5><e5><eC>for </eC></e5><e5><eC>the </eC></e5><e5><eC>Environment </eC></e5><e5><eC>Minister </eC></e5>, <e5>David </e5><e5>Kemp </e5>, said yesterday that the minister was on his way to talks with the <e6>European </e6><e6>Union </e6>in <e4>Brussels </e4>after a formal visit to <e14>Washington </e14>, and that the Government was still committed to <e10>Kyoto </e10>. <br><blue>8</blue><e13><eC>The </eC></e13>Opposition <e13><eC>'s </eC></e13><e13><eC>environment </eC></e13><e13><eC>spokesman </eC></e13>, <e9>Kelvin </e9><e9>Thomson </e9>, said yesterday that <e1>Australia </e1>`` should not follow the <e13>US </e13>position on climate change '' . <br><blue>9</blue>Mr <e2>Blair </e2>told the <e0>ABC </e0>that greenhouse gases were an area where there was an obvious disagreement with <e13><eC>the </eC></e13><e13><eC>US </eC></e13>. <br><blue>10</blue>Asked if the disagreement was also with <e1><eC>Australia </eC></e1><e1><eC>, </eC></e1><e1><eC>Mr </eC></e1><e1><eC>Blair </eC></e1><e2>Blair </e2><e1><eC>said </eC></e1><e1><eC>: </eC></e1><e1><eC>`` </eC></e1>Yes <e1><eC>. </eC></e1><br><blue>11</blue>But I simply say to people , <e1><eC>it </eC></e1>is for individual countries to state their own position . '' <br><blue>12</blue>He was not sure the <e11>Kyoto </e11><e11>Protocol </e11>actually went far enough . <br><blue>13</blue>`` The more I read about climate change , the more concerned I become about this issue . '' <br><blue>14</blue>Copyright @ 2002 <e12>Sydney </e12>Morning Herald <br></div>
